Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00822911 Eh      5.16 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01384498 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04226582 Eh     26.52 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol

Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385492 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00752045 Eh      4.72 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385680 Eh      8.70 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04156898 Eh     26.08 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00753007 Eh      4.73 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385519 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04157698 Eh     26.09 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol

Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385517 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

                  0          1          2          3          4          5

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

freq.    3220.26  E(vib)   ...       0.00 

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol

Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385690 Eh      8.70 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00752984 Eh      4.73 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385530 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04157686 Eh     26.09 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol

Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385514 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol

Final entropy term                ...      0.04157547 Eh     26.09 kcal/mol

------------
NORMAL MODES
------------

These modes are the Cartesian displacements weighted by the diagonal matrix
M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom
Thus, these vectors are normalized but *not* orthogonal

Temperature         ... 298.15 K

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

Summary of contributions to the inner energy U:

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00752707 Eh      4.72 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385523 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol

Final entropy term                ...      0.04157402 Eh     26.09 kcal/mol

NORMAL MODES

M(i,i)=1/sqrt(m[i]) where m[i] is the mass of the displaced atom

Throughout the following assumptions are being made:
  (1) The electronic state is orbitally nondegenerate
      but the spin degeneracy is treated
  (2) There are no thermally accessible electronically excited states
  (3) Hindered rotations indicated by low frequency modes are not
      treated as such but are treated as vibrations and this may
      cause some error
  (4) All equations used are the standard statistical mechanics
      equations for an ideal gas
  (5) All vibrations are strictly harmonic

------------
INNER ENERGY
------------

The inner energy is: U= E(el) + E(ZPE) + E(vib) + E(rot) + E(trans)
    E(el)   - is the total energy from the electronic structure calculation
              = E(kin-el) + E(nuc-el) + E(el-el) + E(nuc-nuc)
    E(ZPE)  - the the zero temperature vibrational energy from the frequency calculation
    E(vib)  - the the finite temperature correction to E(ZPE) due to population
              of excited vibrational states
    E(rot)  - is the rotational thermal energy
    E(trans)- is the translational thermal energy

-------
ENTROPY
-------

The entropy contributions are T*S = T*(S(el)+S(vib)+S(rot)+S(trans))
     S(el)   - electronic entropy
     S(vib)  - vibrational entropy
     S(rot)  - rotational entropy
     S(trans)- translational entropy
The entropies will be listed as multiplied by the temperature to get
units of energy

Electronic entropy                ...      0.00103729 Eh      0.65 kcal/mol
Vibrational entropy               ...      0.00752833 Eh      4.72 kcal/mol
Rotational entropy                ...      0.01385512 Eh      8.69 kcal/mol
Translational entropy             ...      0.01915444 Eh     12.02 kcal/mol
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Final entropy term                ...      0.04157517 Eh     26.09 kcal/mol
